Saoul de corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my house, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he shouldn't drive.
He asked me why.
« You've had too much to drink », I told him, « aren't you afraid of the police? »
Boris replied: « No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it's always useful.»
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police accept bribes, but I was worried that Boris might meet an honest officer.
« Impossible », declared Boris, « to enter the traffic police force, you have to buy your boss's silence.
If you don't pay a bribe, how can you buy your boss's silence?»
Half of Moscow drivers use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
Those fools who try to do things by the rules drown in administrative red tape.
By paying 100 dollars, you can drive around the city without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never at the record levels we see today.
All accept bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one, nowhere, is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
C'était un endroit luxurieux mais similaire au goulag avec ses clôtures haute sécurité et ses gardiens.
En examinant les maisons prétentieuses et décorées avec si peu de goût, je demandais qui les possédais et m'entendis répondre que l'une d'elle appartenait à un adjoint au maire de Moscou, une autre à un chanteur célèbre, une autre encore au fils du procureur de Moscou.
Mais la propriété la plus attrayante appartenait à un modeste fonctionnaire du service des impôts.
La corruption représente maintenant pour la Russie une menace plus grave que la guerre de Tchétchénie.
En fait, la guerre de Tchétchénie n'aurait pas duré aussi longtemps si elle n'était menée par des généraux, des officiers, des fonctionnaires et des policiers corrompus qui revendent armes et provisions aux rebelles.
The Russian television showed recently a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that transported the 120 kilograms of explosives used for the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the hostage rescue operation.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the border guards' dogs from detecting them.
A quite useless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along the way, always for the same reason.
A police officer came to ask him: "Do you know the price?", and the driver replied: "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, which would have taken days for the entire trip.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because the Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all of the so-called "international terrorism" but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels do have ammunition stocks, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more severely?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are themselves corrupt.
Ainsi, those whom one calls « the simple folk » regard this phenomenon with kindness.
They say of their mayor « of course, he steals, but look at all he has done for the town! »
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the conductor both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The conductor stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the spread of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
